0. To install ansible and others like ansible-playbook etc., you can look at tips_ansible elsewhere, or use setup_ansible.sh elsewhere.

1. It looks ansible is very unforgiving on any indent error or ssh requirements, even for local address like 127.0.0.1 or local ifconfig derived values.
However, I was able to run successfully playbook0.yaml without setting any ssh or without using hosts/inventory file.
ansible-playbook  playbook0.yaml
is successful.
But it looks if you use ini file, even for local ip address, ssh config is required.

2. Beyond this, to make the command work with ini file, I had to go through the ssh drill explained elsewhere but showing here:


sudo systemctl status sshd
These 3 commands were not needed as firewall daemon was already there as shown by the above status command:
sudo dnf install openssh-server
sudo systemctl start sshd
sudo systemctl enable sshd

Also did this:
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=ssh
sudo firewall-cmd --reload
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 3072
Needed to do these 2 commands, because I had mistakenly entered y when I should have just entered nothering (just ENTER):
mv y ~/.ssh/id_rsa
mv y.pub ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
 chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa
chmod 644 ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

Last crucial step:
ssh-copy-id rranjan@127.0.0.1
This probably creates a new file authorized_keys in the .ssh folder.

After this, with ini file containig 127.0.0.1, the following command executes beautifully:
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini playbook.yaml

The above command also works beautifully, if I replace  with 192.168.172.138 in ini file, where 192.168.172.138 is IP address of local host. There was NOT any
need for a separate ssh-copy-id rranjan@192.168.172.138

Henceforth, try to not make any change to this hello folder files, keet it in its current pristine form!!

3. One more playbook test for more testing

# Multiple variables
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini mytester.yaml -e "folder_name=my_test folder_state=directory"
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini mytester.yaml -e "folder_name=my_test folder_state=absent"


# Using JSON (very useful for AI Agents)
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini mytester.yaml -e '{"folder_name": "my_test", "folder_state": "directory"}'
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini mytester.yaml -e '{"folder_name": "my_test", "folder_state": "absent"}'

The 4 commands duly and thoroughly tested.

PostScript: 
The mytester.yaml was also tested from AAP environment(deployed on OpenShift), successful in making changes to the RedHat guest (at least 
creating a new folder over there). 
However, I could not down the special steps for configuring on AAP GUI was not noted down succinctly, rather is contained in the word doc
in haphazard manner. I am correcting this fault when doing for eda.
However, for hello (this one) itself, I am trying to note down the steps that were most probably taken here:
Running a playbook from a UI (AAP) is fundamentally different from running it on a terminal because AAP has to provide all the "context" (keys and variables) that you normally provide manually.
(a)
Extra Variables (folder_name and folder_state): 
•	Option A: Static (Always the same): Paste the following into the Variables (Extra Variables) box in the Template definition:
---
folder_name: "my_test"
folder_state: "directory"
(The --- at the top is optional but tells AAP "This is a clean YAML document").
(b) 
Inventory Configuration for Group myHosts etc.

(c) Credentials Twist:
Credentials SSH key:
There are 3 types of Credentials options - 
Don't use password (if you do try password, try the Red hat password, don't copy the key value there, it will not work).
The right way is to "You upload/paste the id_rsa into the SSH Private Key field."

If ever the content in this file is not sufficient to configure playbooks, inventory etc, there is a clumsy word file jottings_aap1 where
you may go, and instead of wading through a lot of junk, try to do a search for "BEGIN COPYPASTE" and "IMPORTANT" etc. Of course, going to the horse's mouth is the last resort, the most clumsy resort probably! 
